 Lowry]]\n|Independent\n|\"Lately\"|| I Could Not Plan This\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|Fabian Mazur\n|Spinnin Records\n|\"Young Once\"\n|N/A\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2018\n|[[Jason Ross (musician)|Jason Ross]]\n|Ophelia\n|\"Don't Give Up On Me\"\n|N/A\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|West Coast Massive\n|Independent \n|\"Until We Die Young\"\n|N/A\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|Frank Pole\n|Armada Music\n|\"Take Back My Love\"\n|N/A\n|featured vocal\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2019\n|Dabin\n|Seeking Blue\n|\"Bloom\"|| Wild Youth\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|PLS&TY\n|Independent \n|\"Summer's Young\"|| N/A\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|[[Jason Ross (musician)|Jason Ross]] feat. [[Melanie Fontana]]\n|Ophelia\n|\"Shelter\"|| N/A\n|co-writer\n|-\n|Witt Lowry\n|Independent \n|\"Debt\"\n|Nevers Road\n|featured vocal\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2020\n|[[Jason Ross (musician)|Jason Ross]]\n|Ophelia\n|\"1000 Faces\"\n\"Someone That I Needed\"\n| 1000 Faces\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|William Black, Fairlane\n|Lowly\n|\"Butterflies\"\n|N/A\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|-\n|Nurko\n|Proximity\n|\"Faith\"\n|N/A\n|co-writer, featured vocal\n|}\n\n==Videography==\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! width=10 | Year\n! width=150 | Title\n! width=100 | Director\n|-\n| 2011 || \"The Broken Ones\" || David McClister\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2013 || \"Over It\" <br><small>(with [[The Crystal Method]])</small>|| Zak Stoltz\n|-\n| \"Stubborn Love\" <br><small>(with [[The Lumineers]])</small>|| Issac Ravishankara\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2017 || \"Don't Look Back\"|| Michael Kaminsky, Braverijah Gregg and Eric Tobin\n|-\n| \"Dead Man\"|| Andrew Ahn\n|-\n|\"Crave\"\n|Andrew Ahn\n|}\n\n===Filmography===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2015\n|Blank Pages\n|Roosevelt\n|2 episodes\n|-\n|2016\n|The Crooked Man\n|Mia\n|TV Movie\n|-\n|2017\n|Criminal Minds\n|Jillian Flanagan\n|Season 12 episode 11\n|-\n|2018\n|Maybe I'm Fine\n|Maya\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[I Ship It]]\n|Amber the fangirl\n|Episode \"Superfans\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web|url=https://medium.com/cuepoint/id-get-to-the-top-of-the-mountain-if-it-would-just-stop-fucking-growing-252af2a6504b|last=Frampton|first=Dia|title=I'd Get to the Top of the Mountain if It Would Just Stop Fucking Growing|work=Cuepoint|publisher=Medium|date=August 30, 2016|accessdate=September 2, 2016}}\n\n{{The Voice (U.S.)}}\n{{Meg & Dia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frampton, Dia}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American women of Korean descent]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Utah]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Salt Lake City]]\n[[Category:People from St. George, Utah]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Utah]]\n[[Category:The Voice (franchise) contestants]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n[[Category:Nettwerk Music Group artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Dia Frampton\n| image            = Dia_frampton_los_angeles.jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = Frampton performing at Tinhorn Flats in [[Hollywood]], [[California]] in May 2015.\n| image_size       = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = \n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1987|10|02}}\n| birth_place      = [[Draper, Utah]], United States\n| death_date       = \n| instrument       = [[Lead singer|vocals]], [[piano]], [[guitar]]\n| genre            = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[folk music|folk]], [[Electronic dance music|EDM]]\n| occupation       = [[Singer-songwriter]]\n| years_active     = 2004\u2013present <!--Meg & Dia was active since 2005 meaning Dia was active since then besides only going solo in 2011-->\n| label            = Pure Noise Records (2019-present), Nettwerk Records (2014-2019) [[Universal Republic Records|Universal Republic]], [[Republic Records|Republic]] (2011-2013)\n| associated_acts  = [[Meg & Dia]], ARCHIS, [[Joseph Trapanese]], [[The Midnight|Tyler Lyle]], [[Lindsey Stirling]], [[tyDi]], [[Jason Ross]]\n| website          = {{URL|http://www.diamusic.net}}\n| image_upright    = \n}}\n'''Dia Frampton'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Dia Frampton: An interview about me by YOU!|url=http://www.diaframpton.blogspot.com/2012/01/interview-about-me-by-you.html|date=January 30, 2012|publisher=diaframpton.blogspot.com}}</ref> (born October 2, 1987) is an American singer, songwriter and topliner. Frampton is the lead singer of the band [[Meg & Dia]], was the runner-up in the [[The Voice (American season 1)|inaugural season]] of ''[[The Voice (American TV series)|The Voice]],'' and is perhaps most know for her presence and collaborations in the [[Electronic dance music|EDM]] world \u2013 having worked with names like [[Illenium]] and [[Kaskade]] among many others.\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life===\nDia Frampton attended [[Dixie High School (Utah)|Dixie High School]] in [[St. George, Utah]] and [[Shadow Ridge High School (Nevada)|Shadow Ridge High School]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. Dia graduated early by homeschooling her senior year, and at the same time attending public school. Dia then moved to Salt Lake City with her sister to further their music career. She cites [[Modest Mouse]], [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers]], [[Joni Mitchell]], [[The Avett Brothers]], [[Rocky Votolato]], [[Ben Folds]], [[Etta James]], [[Death Cab for Cutie]], [[The Cranberries]], and [[Cursive]] as influences.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Dia Frampton|url=http://www.musicgeek.org/wp/2005/06/11/an-interview-with-meg-and-dia|accessdate=January 20, 2008|date=June 11, 2005|publisher=MusicGeek.org}}</ref> During live performances, Frampton plays percussion instruments, such as the [[Cowbell (instrument)|cowbell]] and [[tambourine]], and occasionally a [[Privia|Casio Privia]] keyboard. She almost always performs without shoes on. She also does not like to eat anything within two hours of performing. Her father is an American of English and Dutch ancestry and her mother is Korean, originally from Seoul.\nFrampton often recorded a \"song diary,\" an impromptu recorded song, on her [[MySpace]] page. She explained, \"It was something very raw, and to be honest, something that I was slightly embarrassed to put up because of the quality but I did anyways, for any of our listeners who would care to hear something not hot off the production belt, but something more organic and 'home made.' It made me feel better to share my feelings with people who could connect, and I think that is what happened with many.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.teenvogue.com/story/dia-thinks-in-song|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110330043752/http://www.teenvogue.com/industry/blogs/music/2008/10/dia-thinks-in-song.html|url-status=dead|title=Dia Thinks in Song|first=Cond\u00e9|last=Nast|archivedate=March 30, 2011|website=Teen Vogue}}</ref>\n\n=== 2005-2011: Meg & Dia ===\n\n''Main article: [[Meg & Dia]]''\n\nAlong with her sister Meg, Frampton was part of the five-piece alternative rock band Meg & Dia. The band released their debut album \"Our Home is Gone\" in 2005 (at the time the band was just a two-piece) and later released [[Something Real]] under Doghouse Records, which peaked at #12 on the Billboard Heatseekers Chart. The band found success by promoting their music on [[MySpace]], leading them to become the official MySpace band on the [[Warped Tour 2006]]. \n\nMeg & Dia's profile in the rock scene continued to grow, leading to continued appearances at the Warped Tour, touring with bands such as [[Angels & Airwaves]] and a record deal with [[Warner Bros. Records]]. This deal yielded the pop-rock leaning [[Here, here and here]] , which charted at #103 on the Billboard 200.\n\nIn 2010, Warner Bros. dropped the band, reverting the group back to their indie status. Nonetheless, the band released their fourth studio album, ''[[Cocoon (Meg & Dia album) | Cocoon]]'', which was received positively by fans and critics, but failed to perform well commercially, leading to Dia's manager, Mike Kaminsky, suggesting she audition for ''[[The Voice (U.S.)|The Voice]]''\n\n\n===2011: ''The Voice''===\nDia Frampton was a contestant (and eventual runner-up) on the first season of ''[[The Voice (U.S.)|The Voice]]'' on [[NBC]], introduced as a children's story author. Frampton stated that she had originally joined the show only with the intention of promoting ''[[Cocoon (Meg & Dia album)|Cocoon]]'' and had not expected that she would make it that far in the competition.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dia starts The Voice tour|url=http://meganddia.com/?p=73|website=Meganddia.com|accessdate=January 3, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405193718/http://meganddia.com/?p=73|archive-date=April 5, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> She was selected to be on the team of coach [[Blake Shelton]], who stated, \"when I heard your voice, I started to smile.\" Frampton advanced through the show's quarter-finals and semi-finales after renditions of \"[[Heartless (Kanye West song)|Heartless]]\" and \"[[Losing My Religion]]\". Notably, the aforementioned singles were the highest charting iTunes digital songs by any contestant on ''The Voice'' during its respective voting eligibility period, with \"Inventing Shadows\" topping the charts at No.&nbsp;1. Following the season finale on June 29, 2011, \"Inventing Shadows\" debuted at No.&nbsp;20 on the Billboard Hot 100 with 137,000 downloads sold. As of July 7, 2011 Frampton's ''The Voice'' digital releases have sold 480,000 downloads.<ref>{{cite web|last=Trust|first=Gary |url=http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/tv-film/american-idol-vs-the-voice-who-won-the-1005268192.story |title='American Idol' Vs. 'The Voice': Who Won the Billboard Chart Battle? |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFrampton subsequently won the title of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'''s 2011 'Favourite Reality Show Personality' over Michael Stagliano from the [[Bachelor Pad#Season 2|second season]] of ''[[Bachelor Pad]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last=Carbone|first=Gina|title=Dia Frampton Wins Favorite Reality Show Personality Over Michael Stagliano|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/the-bachelorette/articles/dia-frampton-wins-favorite-reality-show-personality-over-michael-stagilano|accessdate=January 3, 2013|newspaper=wetpaint.com|date=December 12, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Performances on The Voice\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%; line-height:16px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Song\n! scope=\"col\" | Original Artist\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Order\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Blind Audition\n| \"[[Bubbly]]\"\n| [[Colbie Caillat]]\n| May 3, 2011\n| 2.16\n| [[Cee Lo Green]] and [[Blake Shelton]] turned<br>Joined Team Blake\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Battle Rounds\n| \"[[You Can't Hurry Love]]\" (vs. Serabee)\n| [[The Supremes]]\n| May 24, 2011\n| 5.2\n| Saved by Coach\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Quarterfinals\n| \"[[Heartless (Kanye West song)|Heartless]]\"\n| [[Kanye West]]\n| June 7, 2011\n| 7.4\n| Saved by Public Vote\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Semifinals\n| \"[[Losing My Religion]]\"\n| [[R.E.M.]]\n| June 21, 2011\n| 9.3\n| Saved by Coach and Public Vote (106 Points)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" | Finals\n| \"[[I Won't Back Down]]\" <small>(with [[Blake Shelton]])</small>\n| [[Tom Petty]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" | June 28, 2011\n| 11.2\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Runner-up\n|-\n| \"Inventing Shadows\" <small>(Original)</small>\n| Dia Frampton\n| 11.5\n|}\n\n===2011-2013: ''Red'' and embarking on solo career===\n{{listen\n | filename     = Dia Frampton - The Broken Ones.ogg\n | title        = \"The Broken Ones\" (2011)\n | pos = right\n | description  = A 21 second sample of Frampton's debut single, \"The Broken Ones\".\n}}\nFrampton's single, \"The Broken Ones,\" was released on November 15, 2011, and her solo album, ''[[Red (Dia Frampton album)|Red]]'', was released on December 6, 2011. Frampton wrote (or co-wrote) every song on ''[[Red (Dia Frampton album)|Red]]''. Notable co-written songs include \"Billy the Kid\", which she wrote with Mark Foster and Isom Innis, lead singer and keyboard player for [[Foster the People]] respectively, \"Hearts out to Dry,\" which she wrote with her sister, Meg, and \"Bullseye,\" which she wrote with [[Isabella Summers]], the keyboard player for [[Florence and the Machine]].\n\nShe was the opening act for her coach, [[Blake Shelton]], on his Well Lit & Amplified tour. Shelton insisted that she had earned her spot on his tour and he was not doing her any favors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Thompson|first=Gayle|title=Blake Shelton Says Dia Frampton Earned Her Spot on His Tour|url=http://www.theboot.com/2012/02/03/blake-shelton-dia-frampton-tour/|accessdate=January 3, 2013|newspaper=the Boot|date=February 3, 2012}}</ref> She later was a supporting act for [[The Fray]] in their sold out US tour in the Midwest and the West Coast from April to May 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=DIA FRAMPTON Embarks on Sold Out Tour with The Fray|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120427005977/en/DIA-FRAMPTON-Embarks-Sold-Tour-Fray|publisher=Business Wire|accessdate=January 3, 2013}}</ref> Her own solo US tour took place from February to July 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Dia Frampton Tour Dates 2012|url=http://www.concertboom.com/dia-frampton/tour-dates/|website=Concertboom.vom|accessdate=January 3, 2013}}</ref> with Canadian singer/songwriter Andrew Allen as her opening act.<ref>{{cite news|last=Minter|first=Jay|title=Andrew Allen On Tour With The Voice Runner-Up Dia Frampton|url=http://kentonmagazine.com/andrew-allen-on-tour-with-the-voice-runner-up-dia-frampton/|accessdate=January 3, 2013|newspaper=Kenton Magazine|date=January 14, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212132321/http://kentonmagazine.com/andrew-allen-on-tour-with-the-voice-runner-up-dia-frampton/|archive-date=December 12, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nMeg & Dia (whose members had joined Dia on the Blake Shelton tour) confirmed their disbandment in October 2012. <ref>[http://chandler-the-robot.myshopify.com/blogs/news/6801142-whats-going-on-with-meg-and-dia ]{{dead link|date=March 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe covered the Korean song, \"[[Lonely (2NE1 song)|Lonely]]\" by [[2NE1]], as an acoustic ballad in English for allkpop.com to promote her later concert in Seoul, Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title=[Exclusive] Dia Frampton performs her rendition of 2NE1\u2032s \"Lonely\"|url=http://www.allkpop.com/2012/03/exclusive-dia-frampton-performs-her-rendition-of-2ne1s-lonely|publisher=allkpop.com|accessdate=January 3, 2013}}</ref> On December 30, 2012, she sang a solo of \"Heartless\" and performed \"We Are The Champions\" with the final 8 of [[The Voice of Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Voice of US's 1st runner-up arrives in HCMC|url=http://tuoitrenews.vn/cmlink/tuoitrenews/lifestyle/voice-of-us-s-1st-runner-up-arrives-in-hcmc-1.95401|accessdate=January 3, 2013|newspaper=TUOITRENEWS|date=December 29, 2012}}</ref> In January 2013, Dia held a small tour, staging concerts across Southeast Asian countries Vietnam, Singapore, Philippines, Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia.<ref>{{cite web|title=Dia Frampton - Facebook announcement of SEA tour|url=https://www.facebook.com/DiaFramps/posts/462678480433980|publisher=Facebook.com|accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> She also collaborated with Singto Numchok on his singles \"Gift\" and \"Coffee Mate\" in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singto Numchok & Dia Frampton|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/singto-numchok-dia-frampton-mw0002561330|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\n===2013-2015: ARCHIS and new EP===\n[[File:ARCHIS.jpg|thumb|ARCHIS EP Release Show, February 2015]]\nFrampton was featured on \"Heart On the Floor\", which is a track on [[The Summer Set|The Summer Set's]] new album, ''Legendary''. The album was released on April 16, 2013.  She was also featured on [[Never Shout Never|Never Shout Never's]] Christmas EP, singing \"Under the Mistletoe\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/the-xmas-ep/id738210284 |title=iTunes - Music - The Xmas EP by Never Shout Never |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=November 22, 2013 |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> and on [[The Crystal Method|The Crystal Method's]] new single \"Over It\", which was featured on their self-tiled album on January 14, 2014.\nAs of January 2014, Dia is now the opening act for the James Blunt Moon Landing Tour.\nOn April 29, 2014 [[Lindsey Stirling]] released her album ''[[Shatter Me (album)|Shatter Me]]'' on which Dia collaborated on the songs \"We Are Giants\" and \"Shatter Me\". She was also featured in the single \"Stay\" by Australian DJ [[tyDi]] which was released on April 8, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/stay-feat.-dia-frampton-ep/id855568550 |title=iTunes - Music - Stay (feat. Dia Frampton) - EP by tyDi |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=April 8, 2014 |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2014, it was announced that after the release of \"Red,\" Frampton had been dropped from Universal Republic. It was also announced that her new album would be an EP, and not a solo album but under the name of her new band, ARCHIS.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alan Sculley |url=http://expressmilwaukee.com/article-permalink-23394.html |title=Dia Frampton Starts Over with Archis &#124; Music &#124; Shepherd Express |publisher=Expressmilwaukee.com |date=June 4, 2014 |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> Two singles were released on this EP, \"Blood\" and \"I Need You.\" The music video for \"Blood\" was released on June 2, 2014. In August 2014, Frampton announced that Archis had been signed to a new label, and that the EP would be released in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://archismusic.wordpress.com/2014/08/29/archis/ |title=ARCHIS &#124; Archis |publisher=Archismusic.wordpress.com |date=August 29, 2014 |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref>  The EP was produced by her frequent collaborator [[Joseph Trapanese]].\n\nOn March 17, Interscope Records released Insurgent: Original Motion Picture Soundtrack. The song \"Holes In the Sky\" was written by Anthony Gonzalez and Dia Frampton and is performed by [[M83 (band)|M83]] and [[Haim (band)|HAIM]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://divergentsuk.com/2015/02/27/insurgent-soundtrack-list/ |title=Insurgent Soundtrack List! |publisher=Divergents UK |date=February 27, 2015 |accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015-2018: ''Bruises'' LP===\nAfter the release of ARCHIS's EP, the band began working on a full-length [[LP album|LP]], to be released in early 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/archis/status/645670700745822208 |title=ARCHIS on Twitter: \"Happy to say that we are now in the process of recording the new album. It should be done this Nov. & out early 2016 \" |publisher=[[Twitter]] |date=September 20, 2015 |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> However, after releasing a personal essay in August 2016 it was revealed that the LP would be released under her own name and would be titled ''Bruises''. Frampton also revealed that the LP would be produced by [[Dan Heath]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/cuepoint/id-get-to-the-top-of-the-mountain-if-it-would-just-stop-fucking-growing-252af2a6504b#.frmss4g1t |title=I'd Get to the Top of the Mountain if It Would Just Stop Fucking Growing |website=Medium.com |date=August 30, 2016 |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> On October 5, 2016, she premiered the lead single off the LP titled \"Golden Years.\" The single was released on October 7, 2016 as part of an EP with the same name, serving as a preview for the LP which was released on March 3, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|author=Joey Nolfi |url=http://www.ew.com/article/2016/10/05/dia-frampton-golden-years |title=Dia Frampton's Golden Years: Hear her comeback single |website=Ew.com |date=October 5, 2016 |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref>  To coincide with the pre-order of \"Bruises\" becoming available, Frampton released another single, \"Gold & Silver\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/bruises/id1169489011 |title=Bruises by Dia Frampton on Apple Music |website=Itunes.apple.com |date=October 3, 1987 |accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref> After the album's release, Frampton released music videos for the tracks \"Don't Look Back\", \"Dead Man\" and \"Crave\". The latter two being given official single treatment. Throughout 2017 and 2018, Frampton continued to release music in the form of collaborations and guest appearances with other artists. These include Jason Ross, [[Witt Lowry]], [[Illenium]], [[Kaskade]], [[tyDi]], [[Dabin]] and [[Christopher Tin]]. Frampton has also pursued acting, appearing in Criminal Minds and several short films. In December 2017, Frampton released \"Yule Tunes\" as an EP, consisting of 3 cover songs and one original Christmas song - \"The Nice List\".\n\n=== 2019 - present: Meg & Dia reunion ===\nOn April 1st 2019, it was announced that Meg & Dia were to reunite for select dates of the 2019 Warped Tour. On July 26th, the group (now a duo, with former guitarist Gimenez returning as a touring member) surprise-released their  fifth studio album \"happysad\" through Pure Noise Records and released music videos for tracks \"American Spirit\" and \"Teenagers\". The group also embarked on the ''Happysad Tour'' in support of the record. The group also released a Christmas single, \"December, Darling\" on November 1st - with the full length \"December, Darling\" LP arriving on the 15th.\n\nThe group supported [[Amber Liu (singer)|Amber Liu]] on her 24-date North American Tour X in January and February 2020.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"3\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref name=\"US-albums\">{{cite web | url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=dia frampton|chart=Billboard 200}} | title=Dia Frampton Album & Song Chart History: Billboard 200 | publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] | work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] | accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br /><small>Heat</small>]]<br><ref name=\"US-albums\" />\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br /><small>Independent Albums</small>]]<ref name=\"US-albums\" />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Red (Dia Frampton album)|Red]]''\n|\n* Released: December 6, 2011\n* Label: Universal Republic\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 106 || 1\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Bruises''\n|\n* Released: March 3, 2017\n* Label: [[Nettwerk]]\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| \u2014 || 14\n|35\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:15em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:2.5em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=\"US-albums\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Bruises Raw''\n|\n* Released: July 7, 2017\n* Label: [[Nettwerk]]\n* Format: digital download\n| \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |''Yule Tunes''\n|\n* Released: 2017\n* Label: [[Nettwerk]]\n* Format: digital download\n| \u2014\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" st